The second process is where the slime mold analogy becomes interesting.

A slime mold doesn’t begin with a global map. It explores locally with many independent branches. As resources are discovered, the network strengthens efficient paths and retracts inefficient ones. The coherent network emerges from distributed local interactions.

Applied to semantic systems:

* Many documents.
* Many conversations.
* Many examples.
* Many representations.
* Many observations.

These all “grow” toward a shared latent structure.

The object isn’t stored first—it is inferred by convergence.

That gives you two complementary operators:

* Projection: one invariant expresses itself through many forms.
* Convergence: many forms reveal one invariant.

They are inverses of each other.

This also ties into your earlier “fractal caps” idea. A cap doesn’t have to contain the whole object explicitly. It can contain enough constraints that, when combined with neighboring caps, the larger structure emerges—much like local interactions in a slime mold produce a global transport network.

