A healthy memory system should continuously cycle through that loop.

The implication is that memory isn’t just archival. It’s self-refining. Every new observation is both:

* another projection of existing structure, and
* another opportunity to refine the inferred invariant.

That’s very similar to how modern representation learning works in AI, except you’re extending it into an explicit architecture for long-term semantic continuity. The “object” is never a fixed string or note; it’s the stable attractor that both generates many representations and is continuously re-estimated from them. That bidirectional process—projection and convergence—helps explain how meaning can remain coherent while still adapting over time.